{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_mjnb03a1r81o_1","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Gematria\nURL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Methods_of_Hebrew_gematria\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIn numerology, gematria (/ɡəˈmeɪtriə/; Hebrew: גמטריא or גימטריה, gimatriyyā, plural גמטראות or גימטריות, gimatriyyot, borrowed via Aramaic from Koine Greek: γραμμάτια) is the practice of assigning a numerical value to a name, word, or phrase by reading it as a number, or sometimes by using an alphanumeric cipher. The letters of the alphabets involved have standard numerical values, but a word can yield several values if a cipher is used.\n[...]\nAccording to Aristotle\n[...]\n22 BCE), isopsephy\n[...]\nMiletus\n[...]\nThe first evidence\n[...]\n78 BCE\n[...]\nThe most common form of Hebrew gematria is used in the Talmud and Midrash as in Jerusalem Talmud, Genesis Rabba 95:3, and elaborately in Rabbinic literature. It involves reading words and sentences as numbers and\n[...]\nnumerical instead of phonetic values to each letter of the Hebrew alphabet. When read as numbers, they can be compared and\n[...]\nwith other words or phrases; cf. the Hebrew proverb נִכְנַס יַיִן יָצָא סוֹד (Nik̲nas yayin yāṣāʾ soḏ, lit. 'wine entered, secret went out', i.e. in vino veritas). The gematric\n[...]\nof יין ('wine') is 7\n[...]\n(י=\n[...]\n0; י=\n[...]\n0; ן=50) and\n[...]\nis also the gematric\n[...]\nסוד ('secret', ס\n[...]\n0; ו\n[...]\n; ד=4)‎, cf. Babylonian Talmud, tractate\n[...]\nhedrin 38a. Gematria sums can involve single words or lengthy strings of calculations. A\n[...]\nexample of Hebrew numer\n[...]\ngematria is the\n[...]\nIn standard gematria (mispar hechrechi), each letter is given a numerical value between 1 and 400, as shown in the following table. In mispar gadol, the five final letters are given their own values, ranging from 500 to 900. It is possible that this well-known cipher was used to conceal other more hidden ciphers in Jewish texts. For instance, a scribe may discuss a sum using the 'standard gematria' cipher, but may intend the sum to be checked with a different secret cipher.\n[...]\nThere are many different methods used to calculate the numerical value for the individual Hebrew/Aramaic words, phrases or\n[...]\nsentences. Gematria is the 29th of 32 hermeneutical rules countenanced by the Rabbis of the Talmud for valid aggadic interpretation of the Torah. More advanced methods are usually used for\n[...]\nmost significant Biblical verses, prayers, names of God, etc. These\n[...]\n- Mispar hechrachi (absolute value) is the standard method. It assigns the values 1–9, 10–90, 100–400 to the 22 Hebrew letters in order. Sometimes it is also called mispar ha-panim (face number), as opposed to the more complicated mispar ha-akhor (back number).\n[...]\n- Mispar siduri (ordinal value) with each of the 22 letters given a value from 1 to 22.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Gematria - Wikipedia\nURL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gematria\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIn numerology, gematria (/ɡəˈmeɪtriə/; Hebrew: גמטריא or גימטריה, gimatriyyā, plural גמטראות or גימטריות, gimatriyyot, borrowed via Aramaic from Koine Greek: γραμμάτια) is the practice of assigning a numerical value to a name, word, or phrase by reading it as a number, or sometimes by using an alphanumeric cipher. The letters of the alphabets involved have standard numerical values, but a word can yield several values if a cipher is used.\n[...]\nAccording to Aristotle\n[...]\n22 BCE), isopsephy\n[...]\nMiletus\n[...]\nThe first evidence\n[...]\n78 BCE\n[...]\nThe most common form of Hebrew gematria is used in the Talmud and Midrash as in Jerusalem Talmud, Genesis Rabba 95:3, and elaborately in Rabbinic literature. It involves reading words and sentences as numbers and\n[...]\nnumerical instead of phonetic values to each letter of the Hebrew alphabet. When read as numbers, they can be compared and\n[...]\nwith other words or phrases; cf. the Hebrew proverb נִכְנַס יַיִן יָצָא סוֹד (Nik̲nas yayin yāṣāʾ soḏ, lit. 'wine entered, secret went out', i.e. in vino veritas). The gematric\n[...]\nof יין ('wine') is 7\n[...]\n(י=\n[...]\n0; י=\n[...]\n0; ן=50) and\n[...]\nis also the gematric\n[...]\nסוד ('secret', ס\n[...]\n0; ו\n[...]\n; ד=4)‎, cf. Babylonian Talmud, tractate\n[...]\nhedrin 38a. Gematria sums can involve single words or lengthy strings of calculations. A\n[...]\nexample of Hebrew numer\n[...]\ngematria is the\n[...]\nIn standard gematria (mispar hechrechi), each letter is given a numerical value between 1 and 400, as shown in the following table. In mispar gadol, the five final letters are given their own values, ranging from 500 to 900. It is possible that this well-known cipher was used to conceal other more hidden ciphers in Jewish texts. For instance, a scribe may discuss a sum using the 'standard gematria' cipher, but may intend the sum to be checked with a different secret cipher.\n[...]\nThere are many different methods used to calculate the numerical value for the individual Hebrew/Aramaic words, phrases or\n[...]\nsentences. Gematria is the 29th of 32 hermeneutical rules countenanced by the Rabbis of the Talmud for valid aggadic interpretation of the Torah. More advanced methods are usually used for\n[...]\nmost significant Biblical verses, prayers, names of God, etc. These\n[...]\n- Mispar hechrachi (absolute value) is the standard method. It assigns the values 1–9, 10–90, 100–400 to the 22 Hebrew letters in order. Sometimes it is also called mispar ha-panim (face number), as opposed to the more complicated mispar ha-akhor (back number).\n[...]\n- Mispar siduri (ordinal value) with each of the 22 letters given a value from 1 to 22.\n\n---\n\nTitle: What Is Gematria?\nURL: https://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/5541252/jewish/What-Is-Gematria.htm\nPublished: 2022-05-31T16:42:37.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nGematria(from the Greek word*geometria*) refers to a process by which\nnumerical values are ascribed to the letters of the Hebrew alphabet.\n[...]\nAs a simple example, א(Aleph), the first letter of the Hebrew alphabet, has the value of one; and ב(Beit) is the second letter, with the value of two. When they join together to form the Hebrew word אב(which means \"father\"), they have the numerical value of three, since 1+2=3. When two words or\nphrases have the same numerical value, this may indicate a connection. See\nbelow for the exact parameters of how this method may be applied.\n[...]\nAdditionally, Hebrew does not make use of\nArabic numerals. Thereforenumberstoo are written using the Gematria system.\nFor example, if one wanted to write the number 150, one would write ק\"נ‎.1\n[...]\n## In this article\n[...]\n## How Gematria Works\n[...]\nAs seen in the chart below, each letter,\nfrom aleph totav, has a specific numerical value.\n|Letter|Value|Letter|Value|\nAleph א|\n1\n[...]\n|\nLamedל\n|\n30\n|\nBet ב|\n2\n|\nMemמ\n|\n40\n|\nGimelג\n|\n3\n|\nNun נ|\n50\n|\nDaletד\n|\n4\n|\nSamechס\n|\n60\n|\nHeiה\n|\n5\n|\nAyinע\n|\n70\n|\nVavו\n|\n6\n|\nPeh פ|\n80\n|\nZayinז\n|\n7\n|\nTsadi צ|\n90\n|\nChetח\n|\n8\n|\nKufק\n|\n100\n|\nTetט\n|\n9\n|\nReshר\n|\n200\n|\nYudי\n|\n10\n|\nShinש\n|\n300\n|\nKafכ\n|\n20\n|\nTavת\n|\n400\n|\n## Different Methods for Calculating Gematria\n[...]\nThere are various systems for generating\nthe numerical value of each letter (aside from the straightforward method\ndescribed above). We will list some more well-known ones:\n[...]\n> **> Milui **> —A system where each letter is spelled out. Instead of aleph beingone, it is spelled out in Hebrew as אלף, resulting in a total of 111.\n[...]\n> 2\n[...]\n> > **> Mispar Katan **> —Here the zeroes areremoved: yud is 1, kaf is 2, > kuf\n[...]\n> is 1, etc. > > **> Atbash\n[...]\n> **> —Not exclusive to> gematria, but used there too, Atbash is a system in which the first letter ofthe > alef-bet\n[...]\n> (aleph) is replaced by the last letter (tav), the second letter> (bet) by the second-to-last letter (shin), and so on. (The first two pairs ofsubstitutions form the word “> at-bash\n[...]\n> .”) Thus aleph would be switched with tav, and have a value of 400.\n[...]\n> > Althoughthe name *>\n[...]\nven *> (\n[...]\n) is not> mentioned in the\n[...]\ndescend and are progressively diminished, degree by degree, **> by means of substitutions and> transpositions of the\n[...]\n, which are their numericalvalues\n[...]\nThat said, Rabbi Schneur Zalman does\n[...]\npoint out that of the three paths of descent that the Ten Utterances undergo in\n[...]\nthe creation process (substitutions, transpositions and gematri\n[...]\ntwo methods are still using actual letters of thealeph-bet, whereas gematria\n[...]\nis merely the numerical value of the\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Secret Door\nURL: https://bethelkhem.wordpress.com/2022/01/23/introduction-to-numerical-qabalah-a-practical-and-systematic-approach/\nPublished: 2022-01-22T20:44:14.000Z\nAuthor: Alexander Duncan\nHighlights:\nEach number represents a corresponding power or essential dynamic principle of the Absolute. Numbers are all functions of each other, the number 1 or monad being the universal dynamic principle inherent in all numbers. The prime numbers 2, 3, 5, and 7 that cannot be produced by multiplication are also primary principles, but may be derived by addition: 2 = 1 + 1, 3 = 1 + 2, 5= 2 + 3, etc. In addition, 4 = 2 x 2, 6 = 2 x 3, 8 = 2 x 4, 9 = 3 x 3, 10 = 2 x 5, and are thus products of more essential factors. The sefiroth are joined by lines, vectors, or rays, which represent more general energies combining the qualities of the two sefirot, in a descending hierarchy, in which the “higher” sefirah (corresponding to a lower number) is regarded as “emanating” or radiating into the lower principle. These are attributed to the twenty-two letters of the Hebrew alphabet. Including the sefirot, there are therefore 32 principles in total.\n[...]\nThe Hebrew alphabet, along with well Arabic and Greek, which all derive form the original Phoenician alphabet, also correspond to numbers, called*Mispar Hechrachi*(“absolute value”), as well as Hebrew\n[...]\n, Egyptian hieroglyphic symbols, sigils, or glyphs, and the Yetziratic (“World of Formation”) attribution, referring\n[...]\nthe elements, planets, and\n[...]\nof the zodiac. These\n[...]\ndivided into three\n[...]\n(attributed to Air, Water, and Fire), twelve\n[...]\nof the zodiac), and seven double\n[...]\n(the latter corresponding to\n[...]\npirated pronunciations,\n[...]\ntable below.)\n[...]\nThe process of deriving numerical values from Hebrew words is known as gematria, the simplest and most obvious of which is addition. Thus, for example, the name of Keter, spelt KThR, is 20 + 400 + 200 = 620. This is called*Mispar Mispari.*Other useful methods include:\n[...]\n* *Mispar Katan Mispari*(“integral reduced value”), in which the digits of a number are added and re-added until a single digit number remains. Eg., 620 = 6 + 2 = 8. In this way every number may be assigned to a particular sefirah, in this case, Hod, or Mercury.\n[...]\nbeMilui*(““filled\n[...]\nare used. This is called*\n[...]\npar Siduri*(“ordinal\n[...]\nin English Qabalah\n[...]\nNumerical analysis may also proceed by means of factorization and multiplication. Thus, 620 is considered to be the resultant of its constituent factors and their correspondences: 1, 2, 4, 5, 10, 20, 31, 62, 124, 155, and 310, which is in turn a constituent factor of an infinite series, i.e., 620 x 2 = 1240; 620 x 3 = 1860; etc., although in practice three digit numbers are usually the highest considered. Finally, the inherent mathematical characteristics of a number may also be considered. For example, 620 is 22× 5 ×31.\n\n---\n\nTitle: What Is Gematria? | Aish\nURL: https://aish.com/what-is-gematria/\nPublished: 2023-06-05T13:46:58.000Z\nAuthor: hersh\nHighlights:\nGematria numerology is a system whereby each Hebrew letter corresponds to a specific number ranging from one to ninety. These numbers can be calculated to reveal inner meanings found in all sorts of Jewish literature. The focal texts for many scholars being the Talmud and Mishnah, although Gematria can and is applied to any sort of Hebrew text. The first Jewish scholars to derive spiritual interpretations using Gematria were the Kabbalists, the mystical branch of Jewish thought.\n[...]\nContemporary gematria calculation, the mispar hechrachi method (which translates to absolute value), is simple enough. The letters themselves are added up according to their numerical values. Then there are several other systems for gematria calculation used by both ancient and modern scholars, which add to gematria’s extensive systems of interpretation. Listed below are only a few of the methods one can employ for gematria calculation:\n[...]\nGadol (large value\n[...]\nMispar Siduri (ordinal value) gives each letter a number from 1 to 22 in alphabetical order.\n[...]\nMispar Katan (small value) takes the value of the letters and removes the\n[...]\nafter the later letters of the alphabet.\n[...]\nAtbash is a system which calculates value by exchanging each letter’s value for its opposite value, aleph switches with tav, beit would switch with shin, and so on.\n[...]\nThese contemporary equations are used most often, but there are eighteen other methods for valuing Hebrew letters. The original biblical method of gematria calculation has its own letter values as well. These systems add layers of interpretation when combined with overall stories, culture, and legal content of Jewish texts.\n[...]\nthe brilliance of\n[...]\nlet’s\n[...]\nthe biblical method\n[...]\nit is written\n[...]\n700. The numerical\n[...]\nWhile there are numerous systems of value for gematria code the chart below includes the standard values for each letter. Generally, with this set of numbers, amounts are calculated based on addition. However, there are systems that feature certain combinations of letters that can divide, subtract, and multiply amounts.\n[...]\n| --- | --- |\n[...]\nב |\n[...]\n| 3 |\n[...]\nה |\n[...]\nו |\n[...]\nayin ז |\n[...]\nי | 1\n[...]\nכ |\n[...]\n| 40 |\n[...]\nנ | 5\n[...]\nGematria works by applying number values to letters in the Hebrew alphabet. These values are then added, subtracted, multiplied, and divided according to various methods of gematria numerology. The sums of these calculations provide greater insight into the content of the text itself or relating it to other written works.\n\n \n\n Click here to comment on this article\n\n---\n\nTitle: Gematria: The Hebrew Word-Number Cipher – LingoDigest\nURL: https://www.lingodigest.com/gematria-the-hebrew-word-number-cipher/\nPublished: 2025-06-26T15:19:19.000Z\nAuthor: LingoDigest\nHighlights:\nbut equations waiting to be\n[...]\ns the foundation of Gematria\n[...]\ninfluential system of textual interpretation\n[...]\nin the Hebrew language.\n[...]\nGematria\n[...]\na sophisticated hermeneutic tool\n[...]\nand scholars to\n[...]\nlayers of divine meaning hidden within\n[...]\nThe core principle of Gematria is surprisingly straightforward, and its origin is linguistic, not mystical. Unlike modern English, which uses Arabic numerals (1, 2, 3), Ancient Hebrew (like Ancient Greek) did not have a separate system for writing numbers. Instead, the letters of the alphabet, the aleph-bet, did double duty. Each letter was assigned a specific, universally understood numerical value.\n[...]\nThis system, known as Mispar Hechrachi (Standard Gematria), is organized logically:\n[...]\n- The first ten letters (Aleph to Yud) represent units 1 through 10.\n- The next nine letters (Kaf to Tzadi) represent tens 20 through 90.\n- The final three letters (Qof to Tav) represent hundreds 200 through 400.\n[...]\nHere’s a simplified breakdown:\n[...]\n- א (Aleph) = 1\n- ב (Bet) = 2\n- ג (Gimel) = 3\n- …\n- י (Yud) = 10\n- כ (Kaf) = 20\n- ל (Lamed) = 30\n- …\n- ק (Qof) = 100\n- ר (Resh) = 200\n- ש (Shin) = 300\n- ת (Tav) = 400\n[...]\nTo find the gematria of a word, you simply add up the values of its letters. This process transforms any word or phrase into a single integer. The magic, according to practitioners, happens next.\n[...]\nThe foundational belief of Gematria is that words with the same numerical value share an essential, hidden connection. For proponents, particularly within the mystical tradition of Kabbalah, this is no coincidence. If the Torah is a perfect, divinely authored text, then every letter, word, and numerical parallel is intentional—a clue left by the author to guide the reader toward a deeper understanding.\n[...]\n- The value of sulam (ladder) is: Samekh\n[...]\n30) + Mem\n[...]\n40) =\n[...]\n30.\n- The\n[...]\nof Sinai is: Samekh (60) + Yud\n[...]\n10) +\n[...]\n= 130.\n[...]\nWhile Standard Gematria is the most common form, it’s just the tip of the iceberg. The system is a field of study in itself, with dozens of different methods. For example:\n[...]\n- Mispar Katan (Small Gematria): This method reduces each letter’s value to a single digit by removing the trailing zeros. For example, Lamed (30) becomes 3, and Shin (300) also becomes 3. This yields different totals and reveals new connections.\n- Atbash: This is a simple substitution cipher where the first letter of the aleph-bet is swapped for the last, the second for the second-to-last, and so on (Aleph ↔ Tav, Bet ↔ Shin). While primarily a cipher, it has gematrical implications, as the new word can be analyzed for its numerical value and meaning.\n\n---\n\nTitle: 22 Hebrew Letters — Sacred Alphabet | Satyori\nURL: https://satyori.com/kabbalah/letters/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n## The 22 Hebrew Letters\n[...]\nThe sacred alphabet — 22 creative forces through which the universe was spoken into being.\n[...]\nIn the Sefer Yetzirah, God created the universe through 32 paths of wisdom: 10 Sefirot and 22 Hebrew letters. Each letter is not merely a symbol but a force of creation — a channel through which divine energy flows into form. The letters divide into three groups: 3 Mothers (elements), 7 Doubles (planets), and 12 Simples (zodiac), mapping the structure of time, space, and the human soul.\n[...]\n## Mother Letters (Imot)\n[...]\nAlef, Mem, Shin — assigned to Air, Water, and Fire. The three primordial elements from which all creation emerges. The Sefer Yetzirah calls them the \"three mothers\" who gave birth to the universe.\n[...]\n## Double Letters (Kefulot)\n[...]\nSeven letters with two pronunciations (hard and soft), assigned to the seven classical planets and the seven days of creation. They govern the polarities of life: wisdom/folly, wealth/poverty, seed/desolation.\n[...]\n## Simple Letters (Peshutot)\n[...]\nTwelve letters assigned to the twelve zodiac signs, the twelve months, and twelve faculties of the soul. They map the cycle of time and the spectrum of human experience.\n[...]\n## The Letters as Paths\n[...]\nEach Hebrew letter corresponds to one of the 22 paths connecting the Sefirot on the Tree of Life. Where the Sefirot are the nodes of divine consciousness, the letters are the channels between them — the verbs to the Sefirot's nouns. Together, the 10 Sefirot and 22 letters form the 32 paths of wisdom described in the Sefer Yetzirah as the totality of creation's blueprint.\n[...]\nThe Sefirot are the ten emanations that the Hebrew letters connect. Each sefirah is a node of divine consciousness on the Tree.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Hebrew Gematria - Finding numerical relationships in the Texts\nURL: https://hebrew4christians.com/Grammar/Unit_Eight/Hebrew_Gematria/hebrew_gematria.html\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nGematria is a type of numerological study that may be defined as one of more systems for calculating the numerical equivalence of letters, words, and phrases in a particular Hebrew text. These systems are used for the purpose of gaining insight into interrelating concepts and for finding correspondences between words and concepts. Although not identical, gematria is also in the same orbit as the so-called \"Bible Codes\" and \"Equi-distant Letter Sequences\" (ELS) that have become fashionable recently.\n[...]\nAccording to most practitioners, there are several methods used to calculate the numerical value for individual words and phrases. When converted to a number, words/phrases can then be compared to other words/phrases and similarities drawn. I list the most common Hebrew gematria methods below.\n[...]\nEach letter of the Hebrew alphabet is given an assigned number, beginning with one for Aleph, two for Bet, and so on. The tenth letter, Yod, is numerically equivalent to 10, and successive letters equal 20, 30, 40, and so on. The letter Qof near the end of the alphabet, equals 100, and the last letter, Tav, equals 400. This method is sometimes called \"Ragil.\" Using this method, you simply add up each letter of a given word (or phrase) to determine its numerical value: Examples:The value of the word shalom (Shin, Lamed, Vav, Mem) is 300+30+6+40 = 376. The value of the Name YHVH (Yod, Hey, Vav, Hey) is 10+5+6+5 = 26.Note: In the Mispar Mussafi method, the value of a word (or phrase) is the standard gematria value plus the number of letters in the word (or phrase). For example, the value of the word shalom (Shin, Lamed, Vav, Mem) is 300+30+6+40+4 or 380, and the value of the Name YHVH (Yod, Hey, Vav, Hey) is 10+5+6+5+4 or 30.\n[...]\nThe mispar gadol method is the\n[...]\nas the standard method (above) but counts the final forms (\n[...]\nfit) of the Hebrew letters as\n[...]\nnumerical sequence for the alphabet\n[...]\n00 to 900, respectively:\n[...]\nshalom (Shin, Lamed, Vav, Mem) is 300+30+6+600 = 936.The value of the Name YHVH (Yod, Hey, Vav, Hey) is\n[...]\n10+5+6+5 =\n[...]\natan method calculates the value of each\n[...]\nas its standard value but simply\n[...]\nall of the trailing\n[...]\nof Chet is\n[...]\n, Tet is\n[...]\nbut Yod\n[...]\nShin, Lamed, Vav\n[...]\nYHVH\n[...]\nYod, Hey,\n[...]\nYHVH (Yod, Hey, Vav, Hey) as 5+6+5+10\n[...]\nUsing this method, each of the 27 Hebrew letters is assigned an ordinal value from one to twenty-two. For example, Aleph (the first letter) equals 1, Bet (the second letter) equals 2, and so on up to the final Tsade (the last letter), which equals 27: Examples:The value of the word shalom (Shin, Lamed, Vav, Mem) is 21+12+6+24 = 63.The value of the Name YHVH (Yod, Hey, Vav, Hey) is 10+5+6+5 = 26."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4528efae-ffc9-4292-9a69-55bc1c58739b","uuid":"30969ed3-7c13-4b8a-8cf2-9980057e44f8","timestamp":"2026-06-10T18:06:28.696Z","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Gematria\nURL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Methods_of_Hebrew_gematria\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIn numerology, gematria (/ɡəˈmeɪtriə/; Hebrew: גמטריא or גימטריה, gimatriyyā, plural גמטראות or גימטריות, gimatriyyot, borrowed via Aramaic from Koine Greek: γραμμάτια) is the practice of assigning a numerical value to a name, word, or phrase by reading it as a number, or sometimes by using an alphanumeric cipher. The letters of the alphabets involved have standard numerical values, but a word can yield several values if a cipher is used.\n[...]\nAccording to Aristotle\n[...]\n22 BCE), isopsephy\n[...]\nMiletus\n[...]\nThe first evidence\n[...]\n78 BCE\n[...]\nThe most common form of Hebrew gematria is used in the Talmud and Midrash as in Jerusalem Talmud, Genesis Rabba 95:3, and elaborately in Rabbinic literature. It involves reading words and sentences as numbers and\n[...]\nnumerical instead of phonetic values to each letter of the Hebrew alphabet. When read as numbers, they can be compared and\n[...]\nwith other words or phrases; cf. the Hebrew proverb נִכְנַס יַיִן יָצָא סוֹד (Nik̲nas yayin yāṣāʾ soḏ, lit. 'wine entered, secret went out', i.e. in vino veritas). The gematric\n[...]\nof יין ('wine') is 7\n[...]\n(י=\n[...]\n0; י=\n[...]\n0; ן=50) and\n[...]\nis also the gematric\n[...]\nסוד ('secret', ס\n[...]\n0; ו\n[...]\n; ד=4)‎, cf. Babylonian Talmud, tractate\n[...]\nhedrin 38a. Gematria sums can involve single words or lengthy strings of calculations. A\n[...]\nexample of Hebrew numer\n[...]\ngematria is the\n[...]\nIn standard gematria (mispar hechrechi), each letter is given a numerical value between 1 and 400, as shown in the following table. In mispar gadol, the five final letters are given their own values, ranging from 500 to 900. It is possible that this well-known cipher was used to conceal other more hidden ciphers in Jewish texts. For instance, a scribe may discuss a sum using the 'standard gematria' cipher, but may intend the sum to be checked with a different secret cipher.\n[...]\nThere are many different methods used to calculate the numerical value for the individual Hebrew/Aramaic words, phrases or\n[...]\nsentences. Gematria is the 29th of 32 hermeneutical rules countenanced by the Rabbis of the Talmud for valid aggadic interpretation of the Torah. More advanced methods are usually used for\n[...]\nmost significant Biblical verses, prayers, names of God, etc. These\n[...]\n- Mispar hechrachi (absolute value) is the standard method. It assigns the values 1–9, 10–90, 100–400 to the 22 Hebrew letters in order. Sometimes it is also called mispar ha-panim (face number), as opposed to the more complicated mispar ha-akhor (back number).\n[...]\n- Mispar siduri (ordinal value) with each of the 22 letters given a value from 1 to 22.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Gematria - Wikipedia\nURL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gematria\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIn numerology, gematria (/ɡəˈmeɪtriə/; Hebrew: גמטריא or גימטריה, gimatriyyā, plural גמטראות or גימטריות, gimatriyyot, borrowed via Aramaic from Koine Greek: γραμμάτια) is the practice of assigning a numerical value to a name, word, or phrase by reading it as a number, or sometimes by using an alphanumeric cipher. The letters of the alphabets involved have standard numerical values, but a word can yield several values if a cipher is used.\n[...]\nAccording to Aristotle\n[...]\n22 BCE), isopsephy\n[...]\nMiletus\n[...]\nThe first evidence\n[...]\n78 BCE\n[...]\nThe most common form of Hebrew gematria is used in the Talmud and Midrash as in Jerusalem Talmud, Genesis Rabba 95:3, and elaborately in Rabbinic literature. It involves reading words and sentences as numbers and\n[...]\nnumerical instead of phonetic values to each letter of the Hebrew alphabet. When read as numbers, they can be compared and\n[...]\nwith other words or phrases; cf. the Hebrew proverb נִכְנַס יַיִן יָצָא סוֹד (Nik̲nas yayin yāṣāʾ soḏ, lit. 'wine entered, secret went out', i.e. in vino veritas). The gematric\n[...]\nof יין ('wine') is 7\n[...]\n(י=\n[...]\n0; י=\n[...]\n0; ן=50) and\n[...]\nis also the gematric\n[...]\nסוד ('secret', ס\n[...]\n0; ו\n[...]\n; ד=4)‎, cf. Babylonian Talmud, tractate\n[...]\nhedrin 38a. Gematria sums can involve single words or lengthy strings of calculations. A\n[...]\nexample of Hebrew numer\n[...]\ngematria is the\n[...]\nIn standard gematria (mispar hechrechi), each letter is given a numerical value between 1 and 400, as shown in the following table. In mispar gadol, the five final letters are given their own values, ranging from 500 to 900. It is possible that this well-known cipher was used to conceal other more hidden ciphers in Jewish texts. For instance, a scribe may discuss a sum using the 'standard gematria' cipher, but may intend the sum to be checked with a different secret cipher.\n[...]\nThere are many different methods used to calculate the numerical value for the individual Hebrew/Aramaic words, phrases or\n[...]\nsentences. Gematria is the 29th of 32 hermeneutical rules countenanced by the Rabbis of the Talmud for valid aggadic interpretation of the Torah. More advanced methods are usually used for\n[...]\nmost significant Biblical verses, prayers, names of God, etc. These\n[...]\n- Mispar hechrachi (absolute value) is the standard method. It assigns the values 1–9, 10–90, 100–400 to the 22 Hebrew letters in order. Sometimes it is also called mispar ha-panim (face number), as opposed to the more complicated mispar ha-akhor (back number).\n[...]\n- Mispar siduri (ordinal value) with each of the 22 letters given a value from 1 to 22.\n\n---\n\nTitle: What Is Gematria?\nURL: https://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/5541252/jewish/What-Is-Gematria.htm\nPublished: 2022-05-31T16:42:37.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nGematria(from the Greek word*geometria*) refers to a process by which\nnumerical values are ascribed to the letters of the Hebrew alphabet.\n[...]\nAs a simple example, א(Aleph), the first letter of the Hebrew alphabet, has the value of one; and ב(Beit) is the second letter, with the value of two. When they join together to form the Hebrew word אב(which means \"father\"), they have the numerical value of three, since 1+2=3. When two words or\nphrases have the same numerical value, this may indicate a connection. See\nbelow for the exact parameters of how this method may be applied.\n[...]\nAdditionally, Hebrew does not make use of\nArabic numerals. Thereforenumberstoo are written using the Gematria system.\nFor example, if one wanted to write the number 150, one would write ק\"נ‎.1\n[...]\n## In this article\n[...]\n## How Gematria Works\n[...]\nAs seen in the chart below, each letter,\nfrom aleph totav, has a specific numerical value.\n|Letter|Value|Letter|Value|\nAleph א|\n1\n[...]\n|\nLamedל\n|\n30\n|\nBet ב|\n2\n|\nMemמ\n|\n40\n|\nGimelג\n|\n3\n|\nNun נ|\n50\n|\nDaletד\n|\n4\n|\nSamechס\n|\n60\n|\nHeiה\n|\n5\n|\nAyinע\n|\n70\n|\nVavו\n|\n6\n|\nPeh פ|\n80\n|\nZayinז\n|\n7\n|\nTsadi צ|\n90\n|\nChetח\n|\n8\n|\nKufק\n|\n100\n|\nTetט\n|\n9\n|\nReshר\n|\n200\n|\nYudי\n|\n10\n|\nShinש\n|\n300\n|\nKafכ\n|\n20\n|\nTavת\n|\n400\n|\n## Different Methods for Calculating Gematria\n[...]\nThere are various systems for generating\nthe numerical value of each letter (aside from the straightforward method\ndescribed above). We will list some more well-known ones:\n[...]\n> **> Milui **> —A system where each letter is spelled out. Instead of aleph beingone, it is spelled out in Hebrew as אלף, resulting in a total of 111.\n[...]\n> 2\n[...]\n> > **> Mispar Katan **> —Here the zeroes areremoved: yud is 1, kaf is 2, > kuf\n[...]\n> is 1, etc. > > **> Atbash\n[...]\n> **> —Not exclusive to> gematria, but used there too, Atbash is a system in which the first letter ofthe > alef-bet\n[...]\n> (aleph) is replaced by the last letter (tav), the second letter> (bet) by the second-to-last letter (shin), and so on. (The first two pairs ofsubstitutions form the word “> at-bash\n[...]\n> .”) Thus aleph would be switched with tav, and have a value of 400.\n[...]\n> > Althoughthe name *>\n[...]\nven *> (\n[...]\n) is not> mentioned in the\n[...]\ndescend and are progressively diminished, degree by degree, **> by means of substitutions and> transpositions of the\n[...]\n, which are their numericalvalues\n[...]\nThat said, Rabbi Schneur Zalman does\n[...]\npoint out that of the three paths of descent that the Ten Utterances undergo in\n[...]\nthe creation process (substitutions, transpositions and gematri\n[...]\ntwo methods are still using actual letters of thealeph-bet, whereas gematria\n[...]\nis merely the numerical value of the\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Secret Door\nURL: https://bethelkhem.wordpress.com/2022/01/23/introduction-to-numerical-qabalah-a-practical-and-systematic-approach/\nPublished: 2022-01-22T20:44:14.000Z\nAuthor: Alexander Duncan\nHighlights:\nEach number represents a corresponding power or essential dynamic principle of the Absolute. Numbers are all functions of each other, the number 1 or monad being the universal dynamic principle inherent in all numbers. The prime numbers 2, 3, 5, and 7 that cannot be produced by multiplication are also primary principles, but may be derived by addition: 2 = 1 + 1, 3 = 1 + 2, 5= 2 + 3, etc. In addition, 4 = 2 x 2, 6 = 2 x 3, 8 = 2 x 4, 9 = 3 x 3, 10 = 2 x 5, and are thus products of more essential factors. The sefiroth are joined by lines, vectors, or rays, which represent more general energies combining the qualities of the two sefirot, in a descending hierarchy, in which the “higher” sefirah (corresponding to a lower number) is regarded as “emanating” or radiating into the lower principle. These are attributed to the twenty-two letters of the Hebrew alphabet. Including the sefirot, there are therefore 32 principles in total.\n[...]\nThe Hebrew alphabet, along with well Arabic and Greek, which all derive form the original Phoenician alphabet, also correspond to numbers, called*Mispar Hechrachi*(“absolute value”), as well as Hebrew\n[...]\n, Egyptian hieroglyphic symbols, sigils, or glyphs, and the Yetziratic (“World of Formation”) attribution, referring\n[...]\nthe elements, planets, and\n[...]\nof the zodiac. These\n[...]\ndivided into three\n[...]\n(attributed to Air, Water, and Fire), twelve\n[...]\nof the zodiac), and seven double\n[...]\n(the latter corresponding to\n[...]\npirated pronunciations,\n[...]\ntable below.)\n[...]\nThe process of deriving numerical values from Hebrew words is known as gematria, the simplest and most obvious of which is addition. Thus, for example, the name of Keter, spelt KThR, is 20 + 400 + 200 = 620. This is called*Mispar Mispari.*Other useful methods include:\n[...]\n* *Mispar Katan Mispari*(“integral reduced value”), in which the digits of a number are added and re-added until a single digit number remains. Eg., 620 = 6 + 2 = 8. In this way every number may be assigned to a particular sefirah, in this case, Hod, or Mercury.\n[...]\nbeMilui*(““filled\n[...]\nare used. This is called*\n[...]\npar Siduri*(“ordinal\n[...]\nin English Qabalah\n[...]\nNumerical analysis may also proceed by means of factorization and multiplication. Thus, 620 is considered to be the resultant of its constituent factors and their correspondences: 1, 2, 4, 5, 10, 20, 31, 62, 124, 155, and 310, which is in turn a constituent factor of an infinite series, i.e., 620 x 2 = 1240; 620 x 3 = 1860; etc., although in practice three digit numbers are usually the highest considered. Finally, the inherent mathematical characteristics of a number may also be considered. For example, 620 is 22× 5 ×31.\n\n---\n\nTitle: What Is Gematria? | Aish\nURL: https://aish.com/what-is-gematria/\nPublished: 2023-06-05T13:46:58.000Z\nAuthor: hersh\nHighlights:\nGematria numerology is a system whereby each Hebrew letter corresponds to a specific number ranging from one to ninety. These numbers can be calculated to reveal inner meanings found in all sorts of Jewish literature. The focal texts for many scholars being the Talmud and Mishnah, although Gematria can and is applied to any sort of Hebrew text. The first Jewish scholars to derive spiritual interpretations using Gematria were the Kabbalists, the mystical branch of Jewish thought.\n[...]\nContemporary gematria calculation, the mispar hechrachi method (which translates to absolute value), is simple enough. The letters themselves are added up according to their numerical values. Then there are several other systems for gematria calculation used by both ancient and modern scholars, which add to gematria’s extensive systems of interpretation. Listed below are only a few of the methods one can employ for gematria calculation:\n[...]\nGadol (large value\n[...]\nMispar Siduri (ordinal value) gives each letter a number from 1 to 22 in alphabetical order.\n[...]\nMispar Katan (small value) takes the value of the letters and removes the\n[...]\nafter the later letters of the alphabet.\n[...]\nAtbash is a system which calculates value by exchanging each letter’s value for its opposite value, aleph switches with tav, beit would switch with shin, and so on.\n[...]\nThese contemporary equations are used most often, but there are eighteen other methods for valuing Hebrew letters. The original biblical method of gematria calculation has its own letter values as well. These systems add layers of interpretation when combined with overall stories, culture, and legal content of Jewish texts.\n[...]\nthe brilliance of\n[...]\nlet’s\n[...]\nthe biblical method\n[...]\nit is written\n[...]\n700. The numerical\n[...]\nWhile there are numerous systems of value for gematria code the chart below includes the standard values for each letter. Generally, with this set of numbers, amounts are calculated based on addition. However, there are systems that feature certain combinations of letters that can divide, subtract, and multiply amounts.\n[...]\n| --- | --- |\n[...]\nב |\n[...]\n| 3 |\n[...]\nה |\n[...]\nו |\n[...]\nayin ז |\n[...]\nי | 1\n[...]\nכ |\n[...]\n| 40 |\n[...]\nנ | 5\n[...]\nGematria works by applying number values to letters in the Hebrew alphabet. These values are then added, subtracted, multiplied, and divided according to various methods of gematria numerology. The sums of these calculations provide greater insight into the content of the text itself or relating it to other written works.\n\n \n\n Click here to comment on this article\n\n---\n\nTitle: Gematria: The Hebrew Word-Number Cipher – LingoDigest\nURL: https://www.lingodigest.com/gematria-the-hebrew-word-number-cipher/\nPublished: 2025-06-26T15:19:19.000Z\nAuthor: LingoDigest\nHighlights:\nbut equations waiting to be\n[...]\ns the foundation of Gematria\n[...]\ninfluential system of textual interpretation\n[...]\nin the Hebrew language.\n[...]\nGematria\n[...]\na sophisticated hermeneutic tool\n[...]\nand scholars to\n[...]\nlayers of divine meaning hidden within\n[...]\nThe core principle of Gematria is surprisingly straightforward, and its origin is linguistic, not mystical. Unlike modern English, which uses Arabic numerals (1, 2, 3), Ancient Hebrew (like Ancient Greek) did not have a separate system for writing numbers. Instead, the letters of the alphabet, the aleph-bet, did double duty. Each letter was assigned a specific, universally understood numerical value.\n[...]\nThis system, known as Mispar Hechrachi (Standard Gematria), is organized logically:\n[...]\n- The first ten letters (Aleph to Yud) represent units 1 through 10.\n- The next nine letters (Kaf to Tzadi) represent tens 20 through 90.\n- The final three letters (Qof to Tav) represent hundreds 200 through 400.\n[...]\nHere’s a simplified breakdown:\n[...]\n- א (Aleph) = 1\n- ב (Bet) = 2\n- ג (Gimel) = 3\n- …\n- י (Yud) = 10\n- כ (Kaf) = 20\n- ל (Lamed) = 30\n- …\n- ק (Qof) = 100\n- ר (Resh) = 200\n- ש (Shin) = 300\n- ת (Tav) = 400\n[...]\nTo find the gematria of a word, you simply add up the values of its letters. This process transforms any word or phrase into a single integer. The magic, according to practitioners, happens next.\n[...]\nThe foundational belief of Gematria is that words with the same numerical value share an essential, hidden connection. For proponents, particularly within the mystical tradition of Kabbalah, this is no coincidence. If the Torah is a perfect, divinely authored text, then every letter, word, and numerical parallel is intentional—a clue left by the author to guide the reader toward a deeper understanding.\n[...]\n- The value of sulam (ladder) is: Samekh\n[...]\n30) + Mem\n[...]\n40) =\n[...]\n30.\n- The\n[...]\nof Sinai is: Samekh (60) + Yud\n[...]\n10) +\n[...]\n= 130.\n[...]\nWhile Standard Gematria is the most common form, it’s just the tip of the iceberg. The system is a field of study in itself, with dozens of different methods. For example:\n[...]\n- Mispar Katan (Small Gematria): This method reduces each letter’s value to a single digit by removing the trailing zeros. For example, Lamed (30) becomes 3, and Shin (300) also becomes 3. This yields different totals and reveals new connections.\n- Atbash: This is a simple substitution cipher where the first letter of the aleph-bet is swapped for the last, the second for the second-to-last, and so on (Aleph ↔ Tav, Bet ↔ Shin). While primarily a cipher, it has gematrical implications, as the new word can be analyzed for its numerical value and meaning.\n\n---\n\nTitle: 22 Hebrew Letters — Sacred Alphabet | Satyori\nURL: https://satyori.com/kabbalah/letters/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n## The 22 Hebrew Letters\n[...]\nThe sacred alphabet — 22 creative forces through which the universe was spoken into being.\n[...]\nIn the Sefer Yetzirah, God created the universe through 32 paths of wisdom: 10 Sefirot and 22 Hebrew letters. Each letter is not merely a symbol but a force of creation — a channel through which divine energy flows into form. The letters divide into three groups: 3 Mothers (elements), 7 Doubles (planets), and 12 Simples (zodiac), mapping the structure of time, space, and the human soul.\n[...]\n## Mother Letters (Imot)\n[...]\nAlef, Mem, Shin — assigned to Air, Water, and Fire. The three primordial elements from which all creation emerges. The Sefer Yetzirah calls them the \"three mothers\" who gave birth to the universe.\n[...]\n## Double Letters (Kefulot)\n[...]\nSeven letters with two pronunciations (hard and soft), assigned to the seven classical planets and the seven days of creation. They govern the polarities of life: wisdom/folly, wealth/poverty, seed/desolation.\n[...]\n## Simple Letters (Peshutot)\n[...]\nTwelve letters assigned to the twelve zodiac signs, the twelve months, and twelve faculties of the soul. They map the cycle of time and the spectrum of human experience.\n[...]\n## The Letters as Paths\n[...]\nEach Hebrew letter corresponds to one of the 22 paths connecting the Sefirot on the Tree of Life. Where the Sefirot are the nodes of divine consciousness, the letters are the channels between them — the verbs to the Sefirot's nouns. Together, the 10 Sefirot and 22 letters form the 32 paths of wisdom described in the Sefer Yetzirah as the totality of creation's blueprint.\n[...]\nThe Sefirot are the ten emanations that the Hebrew letters connect. Each sefirah is a node of divine consciousness on the Tree.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Hebrew Gematria - Finding numerical relationships in the Texts\nURL: https://hebrew4christians.com/Grammar/Unit_Eight/Hebrew_Gematria/hebrew_gematria.html\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nGematria is a type of numerological study that may be defined as one of more systems for calculating the numerical equivalence of letters, words, and phrases in a particular Hebrew text. These systems are used for the purpose of gaining insight into interrelating concepts and for finding correspondences between words and concepts. Although not identical, gematria is also in the same orbit as the so-called \"Bible Codes\" and \"Equi-distant Letter Sequences\" (ELS) that have become fashionable recently.\n[...]\nAccording to most practitioners, there are several methods used to calculate the numerical value for individual words and phrases. When converted to a number, words/phrases can then be compared to other words/phrases and similarities drawn. I list the most common Hebrew gematria methods below.\n[...]\nEach letter of the Hebrew alphabet is given an assigned number, beginning with one for Aleph, two for Bet, and so on. The tenth letter, Yod, is numerically equivalent to 10, and successive letters equal 20, 30, 40, and so on. The letter Qof near the end of the alphabet, equals 100, and the last letter, Tav, equals 400. This method is sometimes called \"Ragil.\" Using this method, you simply add up each letter of a given word (or phrase) to determine its numerical value: Examples:The value of the word shalom (Shin, Lamed, Vav, Mem) is 300+30+6+40 = 376. The value of the Name YHVH (Yod, Hey, Vav, Hey) is 10+5+6+5 = 26.Note: In the Mispar Mussafi method, the value of a word (or phrase) is the standard gematria value plus the number of letters in the word (or phrase). For example, the value of the word shalom (Shin, Lamed, Vav, Mem) is 300+30+6+40+4 or 380, and the value of the Name YHVH (Yod, Hey, Vav, Hey) is 10+5+6+5+4 or 30.\n[...]\nThe mispar gadol method is the\n[...]\nas the standard method (above) but counts the final forms (\n[...]\nfit) of the Hebrew letters as\n[...]\nnumerical sequence for the alphabet\n[...]\n00 to 900, respectively:\n[...]\nshalom (Shin, Lamed, Vav, Mem) is 300+30+6+600 = 936.The value of the Name YHVH (Yod, Hey, Vav, Hey) is\n[...]\n10+5+6+5 =\n[...]\natan method calculates the value of each\n[...]\nas its standard value but simply\n[...]\nall of the trailing\n[...]\nof Chet is\n[...]\n, Tet is\n[...]\nbut Yod\n[...]\nShin, Lamed, Vav\n[...]\nYHVH\n[...]\nYod, Hey,\n[...]\nYHVH (Yod, Hey, Vav, Hey) as 5+6+5+10\n[...]\nUsing this method, each of the 27 Hebrew letters is assigned an ordinal value from one to twenty-two. For example, Aleph (the first letter) equals 1, Bet (the second letter) equals 2, and so on up to the final Tsade (the last letter), which equals 27: Examples:The value of the word shalom (Shin, Lamed, Vav, Mem) is 21+12+6+24 = 63.The value of the Name YHVH (Yod, Hey, Vav, Hey) is 10+5+6+5 = 26.","_meta":{"searchTime":929.1}}]}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_mjnb03a1r81o_2","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: The History of Numerology: Origins, Pythagoras & More\nURL: https://numerologist.com/numerology/the-history-of-numerology\nPublished: 2010-02-15T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIt was the Greek mathematician and mystic Pythagoras, who lived in the sixth century B.C. who is credited with bringing to the attention of the world by stating that “number is the ruler of forms and ideas and the cause of gods and daemons.”\n[...]\n- Pythagoras laid the foundation - The Greek mathematician from the 6th century B.C. gave us the number-meaning system most numerologists still use today.\n[...]\n- Multiple cultures shaped the tradition - Babylonian, Egyptian, Jewish Kabbalistic, Indian Vedic, and Chinese traditions all contributed to what you now know as numerology.\n[...]\nThe truth is modern numerology is a mishmash of evolutionary contributions from a variety of different teachers and cultures including Babylonian magic, astrological philosophy from Hellenistic Alexandria, the Jewish Kabbalah. The Indian Vedas, the Chinese “Circle of the Dead”, and the Egyptian “Book of the Master of the Secret House” (Ritual of the Dead). A lot of these texts are sacred and misunderstood and were not really available to the public until this day. Of course that means that there were many famous numerologists in the world working in all of these cultures - it is just that their achievements are lost in the sands of time.\n[...]\nsecond most famous “found\n[...]\n” of numerology was St\n[...]\nhad numerical relationships\n[...]\nand investigate the\n[...]\n900s and written\n[...]\nDow Balliett\n[...]\nas a Pythagorean system.\n[...]\nNo single person invented numerology. The practice stretches back thousands of years across multiple civilizations. Pythagoras is often called the father of modern numerology because he formalized the idea that numbers carry distinct vibrations and meanings. But Babylonian, Egyptian, and Indian cultures were working with numerical symbolism long before he came along.\n[...]\nNumerology is at least 4,000 years old. Ancient Babylonian texts and Egyptian scrolls like the Book of the Master of the Secret House contain early numerical systems. The Pythagorean framework you encounter most often dates to around 500 B.C., making even the 'modern' version roughly 2,500 years old.\n[...]\n### What is the difference between Pythagorean and Chaldean numerology?\n[...]\nPythagorean numerology assigns numbers 1 through 9 to the letters of the alphabet in sequence and is the most widely used system today. Chaldean numerology, rooted in ancient Babylonian practice, assigns numbers based on the vibrational quality of each letter and does not use the number 9 in letter assignments. Most online calculators use the Pythagorean method.\n\n---\n\nTitle: History of Numerology - Kabbalah, Chaldean, Pythagorean, Chinese..\nURL: https://www.mypandit.com/numerology/history/\nPublished: 2021-06-04T09:58:33.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nSince the ages, many countries follow the basic concept of numerology. Countries like India, Greece, Italy, Japan, China, and ancient Egypt have already started using Numerology concepts. Chaldean Numerology and Kabbalah Numerology were the two methods often used in ancient times. The Greek philosopher Pythagoras later became the father of numerology. He is the one who developed the Pythagorean Numerology, which is also known as modern numerology. In the past, Pythagoras and other philosophers believed mathematics had more accessible concepts to classify than physics. They established schools for mathematics, astrology and music in Italy. Pythagoras was mostly fascinated with the principles of numbers and concepts of mathematics rather than solving problems. He firmly believed that numbers could expose the entire universe. However, his theories helped other philosophers to look into the concept, and even in mathematics, his theorems are the base of any high-level mathematics.\n[...]\nThe Chaldean system is mainly associated with every aspect of astrology. The Chaldeans were known as ancient Babylonian people, who used to recognize the energy change based on their way of speaking or thinking. This numerology is also associated with its branches of the Vedic system. This numerology works on only 1 to 8 numbers as the number 9 represents infinity. The Chaldean system has the same master numbers as the one in the Pythagorean system. Master numbers like 11, 22, 33 cannot be reduced to a single number as they have their own different paths. The Pythagorean system also borrowed the principles from Chaldean Numerology, but both systems’ calculations don’t correlate with each other. In Chaldean numerology, single-digit reveal an individual’s outer personality while double digits describe inner personality. The first name represents the person’s social status, the middle name indicates soul energy, and the last name demonstrates your self-image.\n[...]\nThis western numerology system was founded by a Greek philosopher and mathematician named Pythagoras. His interest in music led him to find the different vibration of numbers in string instruments, which could be explained mathematically. His mathematics theorems are the base in modern geometry. He used to predict the events of some locations and practised divine fates of individuals. In the Pythagorean system, alphabets were assigned to numbers in sequence order. Each alphabet is in sequence from 1 to 9 numbers. This method uses birth name and date of birth to examine the relationship between them. If an individual changes their name, they earn a new number. Their new name will undoubtedly make changes in personality and nature.\n[...]\n11,\n\n---\n\nTitle: What Is Numerology? The Complete Guide to Life Path...\nURL: https://thalira.com/blogs/quantum-codex/numerology-life-path-numbers-destiny\nPublished: 2025-01-20T08:01:30.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nNumerology is\n[...]\nas carriers of\n[...]\nand expression number (from full name) reveal core qualities and\n[...]\n- Numerology derives from Pythagorean philosophy (c. 570-495 BCE): \"all is number\" as a metaphysical claim, not merely mathematical observation\n[...]\n- Three principal systems: Pythagorean (sequential A=1...Z=8), Chaldean (vibrational, Babylonian origin, no 9 in letter values), and Kabbalistic gematria (Hebrew letter-number identity)\n[...]\n- Master numbers 11, 22, and 33 carry elevated\n[...]\npotential and correspondingly greater\n[...]\n; not reduced further in\n[...]\n- The life path number (from\n[...]\nnumber (from\n[...]\n) are the two primary\n[...]\nin most systems\n[...]\nThe Pythagorean school of southern Italy (6th-5th century BCE) is the acknowledged source of Western numerology's philosophical foundations. Pythagoras of Samos (c. 570-495 BCE) taught that the cosmos is structured by number and mathematical ratio. The school's motto, \"all is number,\" was not a mathematical reduction of reality but a metaphysical claim: numbers are the formal principles that give reality its structure, intelligibility, and beauty.\n[...]\nThe Chaldean system draws on Babylonian and Mesopotamian number mysticism, which assigned planetary rulerships to numbers and understood the first nine numbers as encoding cosmic forces corresponding to the seven visible planets plus the nodes of the lunar orbit. This system was transmitted through Hellenistic astrology into the Arabic tradition and eventually into European occultism.\n[...]\n| System | Origin | Letter Assignment | Distinctive Feature |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Pythagorean | Greek, 6th century BCE | Sequential: A=1, B=2...Z=8 (cycling) | Most widely used; simple sequential assignment |\n| Chaldean | Babylonian; popularised by Cheiro | Vibrational: A=1, B=2, C=3, D=4, E=5, F=8, G=3, H=5, I=1... (complex) | No 9 in letter values; emphasises spoken name over birth name |\n| Kabbalistic Gematria | Hebrew Kabbalah; ancient | Hebrew letter-number identity (aleph=1, bet=2...) | Works with Hebrew text and names; connects to Tree of Life sephiroth |\n[...]\nPythagorean numerology assigns numbers 1-9 sequentially to the letters A-Z and is the most widely used Western system. Chaldean numerology, considered older and rooted in ancient Babylonian/Mesopotamian traditions, assigns numbers based on vibrational resonance rather than sequence, resulting in different letter-number correspondences. Chaldean numerology does not use the number 9 in letter assignments, and gives greater emphasis to the name by which a person is actually called rather than their full birth name. Many professional numerologists consider the Chaldean system more nuanced but more complex to learn.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Pythagorean vs Chaldean Numerology — Meaning, Strengths, Career, Love, Spiritual Significance | Insights by Omkar\nURL: https://insightsbyomkar.com/numerology/pythagorean-vs-chaldean\nPublished: 2026-04-12T00:45:59.000Z\nAuthor: Omkar\nHighlights:\nTwo ancient systems, two different maps of the same territory — Pythagorean numerology assigns letters in sequence,\n[...]\nfollows sound vibration.\n[...]\nNumerology is not\n[...]\nmost widely practiced in\n[...]\nPythagorean numerology (\n[...]\ncalled Western or Modern numerology) is the system used throughout this library and in the vast majority of English-language numerology resources. It assigns numbers 1 through 9 to the letters of the alphabet in sequential order: A=1, B=2, C=3 through I=9, then the cycle repeats with J=1, K=2, and so on through Z=8.\n[...]\nChaldean numerology (also called Mystic numerology) is older, originating in ancient Mesopotamia. It assigns numbers 1 through 8 to letters based on their vibrational quality rather than their alphabetical order — and it does not use the number 9 in letter assignments at all, considering 9 too sacred to assign to any letter.\n[...]\nThe Pythagorean approach is mathematical and orderly. Letters are assigned numbers based on their position in the alphabet. There is an elegant logic to the system: A=1 through I=9, then J=1 through R=9, then S=1 through Z=8. The pattern is simple, learnable, and consistent. This reflects the Pythagorean philosophical tradition, which understood the universe as fundamentally ordered and believed that mathematical relationships underlie all of reality.\n[...]\nThe Chaldean approach is vibrational and intuitive. Letters are assigned numbers based on the sound they produce and the energetic quality of that sound — not their alphabetical position. This means the Chaldean table looks less orderly but, practitioners argue, captures something the sequential assignment misses: the actual energetic frequency of the letter as it is spoken.\n[...]\nThe existence of two major systems — and others beyond them (Kabbalistic, Tamil, Chinese) — is itself a spiritual teaching. It says: reality is richer than any single map can capture. Every system illuminates some aspects of truth and obscures others. The mature spiritual practitioner holds their chosen system with conviction and humility simultaneously.\n[...]\nPythagorean numerology, with its roots in Greek philosophy, tends toward the logos — ordered, rational, structural. Chaldean numerology, with its roots in Mesopotamian mysticism, tends toward the numinous — vibrational, intuitive, mysterious.\n[...]\nYes. Chaldean numerology traces its roots to ancient Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq), predating Pythagoras by centuries. Pythagorean numerology, while named for the 6th-century BCE Greek philosopher, was systematized in its modern form in the 19th and 20th centuries. However, age alone does not determine accuracy — both systems have evolved through centuries of interpretive refinement.\n\n---\n\nTitle: N/A\nURL: https://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1529408/1/Pythagoreans-number&numerology.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\noreans are supposed to have had an interest in numerology. There\n[...]\nis a need here\n[...]\nbe careful about\n[...]\nsort of numerology is ascribed to\n[...]\nPythagoreans, as there are many types of numerology and as we have seen \nPythagoreanism was quite a diverse phenomenon encompassing a good many \ndifferent ideas and attitudes. The first thing to say is that while there is some\u0002thing in the modern world called ‘Pythagorean Numerology’, as far as we know\n[...]\nthis sort of numerology was not practised by the Pythagoreans. The basic idea of\n[...]\nmodern Pythagorean numerology is that we can tell something about someone’s \ncharacter or fate by substituting numbers for the letters of their name (a = 1, \nb = 2, etc.) and then manipulating those numbers, along with the numbers of \ntheir birthday, to reach a single figured integer. So for simplicity, let us take \nsomeone called Aaron Abbs, born 01/02/2000.\n[...]\nhere is entirely arbitrary and can be made more\n[...]\ncomplex and the interpretation of the key numbers made more complex to give\n[...]\nan air of expertise or mystery, but the basic principles remain\n[...]\nthe same. However, much as modern numerologists would like to give their\n[...]\npractice ancient authority or mystique by linking it to early Pythagoreans, they \nwere simply\n[...]\nnumerologists of this sort.24\n[...]\nThis is not to say that the Pythagoreans were uninterested in what we might \nterm numerology. This is probably better put by saying that the Pythagoreans \nwere interested in all aspects of numbers and their properties. They did not \nreally have a distinction between a purely mathematical property of a number \nand numerology, which is not surprising in their historical context. Indeed, it is \nnot as easy as it might seem, even today, to give a watertight definition of what \nis mathematical and what is numerological. Modern philosopher David Stove \nhas commented that:\n[...]\nit is easy to rule out the ‘Pythagorean’ numerology we have seen above,\n[...]\nthe fact is that numbers do have some interesting properties and it is not so\n[...]\nthe line between the mathematical and the numerological – and it\n[...]\ncertainly would not have been easy for the Pythagoreans.\n[...]\nThat some Pythagoreans were interested in what\n[...]\nThey did attribute\n[...]\n-mathematical properties to numbers\n[...]\nwith mar\u0002riage and 10 was seen as a divine or special number. There are some important\n[...]\nfind in the Pythagoreans\n[...]\nto apply what are thought to\n[...]\nys of 1, 2,\n[...]\nsome aspects of\n[...]\nthat we discussed\n[...]\nand indeed Plato, have been said to employ\n[...]\nIn a sense that is true, as both employ numbers in their\n\n---\n\nTitle: Origins of Numerology - Divination Foundation\nURL: https://divination.com/origins-of-numerology/\nPublished: 2007-05-16T19:49:59.000Z\nAuthor: nayana\nHighlights:\nKabbalic Numerology—which is often used to interpret names—originally derived from Hebrew mysticism, is an outgrowth of the Hebrew alphabet with its twenty-two vibrations. Later it was adapted for the Greek alphabet, then the Roman alphabet. Thirteenth century Kabbalists believed that the Old Testament was written in a secret code inspired by God. They used Numerology as a tool to decipher this code. It also happens that twenty-two-base Numerology adds a significant dimension to the interpretation of the twenty-two Trump cards of the Tarot deck.\n[...]\nChaldean Numerology has closer ties to Astrology, having originated in Mesopotamia, which was also the birthplace of Western Astrology. It is also related to the Vedic system of India, as well as the Kabbalah. The basis of Chaldean Numerology is that each letter has a unique vibration and is assigned a number from 1 to 8 based on its energetic quality. The number 9 is kept separate from the other numbers—except when it appears as a from the other numbers—except when it appears as a sum of vibrations—because it is considered the most sacred number. In Chaldean Numerology, single digits reveal the outer nature of a person, while double digits describe inner qualities.\n[...]\nThe third and most popular form of Numerology is the method developed by Pythagoras, the Greek mathematician and metaphysician of the 6th century B.C. Pythagoras is famous for his formulation of the Pythagorean theorem, which calculates the hypotenuse of a right triangle, a basic construct of modern geometry. According to legend, Pythagoras was the founder of Numerology and practiced it to divine the fates of individuals, predict the events of certain locations, and use name changing as a means to alter destiny. In the Pythagorean system, numbers were assigned to letters in the Greek alphabet based on their position in the sequence. Pythagorean Numerology generally uses both the name and the date of birth, and then examines the relationships between them, much like the Chaldean method. The basic vibrations are 1 through 9, and the master vibrations are 11 and 22, which are never reduced to a single digit. In the 1800s, when scientific discoveries regarding magnetism, light, and electricity were progressing rapidly, the idea that energy patterns of vibrations corresponded to numbers became popular. Overall, the use of Numerology for self-knowledge and divination has continued to blossom with undying popularity."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4528efae-ffc9-4292-9a69-55bc1c58739b","uuid":"7d950867-69f7-425d-8921-e602f1e00aa6","timestamp":"2026-06-10T18:06:29.968Z","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: The History of Numerology: Origins, Pythagoras & More\nURL: https://numerologist.com/numerology/the-history-of-numerology\nPublished: 2010-02-15T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIt was the Greek mathematician and mystic Pythagoras, who lived in the sixth century B.C. who is credited with bringing to the attention of the world by stating that “number is the ruler of forms and ideas and the cause of gods and daemons.”\n[...]\n- Pythagoras laid the foundation - The Greek mathematician from the 6th century B.C. gave us the number-meaning system most numerologists still use today.\n[...]\n- Multiple cultures shaped the tradition - Babylonian, Egyptian, Jewish Kabbalistic, Indian Vedic, and Chinese traditions all contributed to what you now know as numerology.\n[...]\nThe truth is modern numerology is a mishmash of evolutionary contributions from a variety of different teachers and cultures including Babylonian magic, astrological philosophy from Hellenistic Alexandria, the Jewish Kabbalah. The Indian Vedas, the Chinese “Circle of the Dead”, and the Egyptian “Book of the Master of the Secret House” (Ritual of the Dead). A lot of these texts are sacred and misunderstood and were not really available to the public until this day. Of course that means that there were many famous numerologists in the world working in all of these cultures - it is just that their achievements are lost in the sands of time.\n[...]\nsecond most famous “found\n[...]\n” of numerology was St\n[...]\nhad numerical relationships\n[...]\nand investigate the\n[...]\n900s and written\n[...]\nDow Balliett\n[...]\nas a Pythagorean system.\n[...]\nNo single person invented numerology. The practice stretches back thousands of years across multiple civilizations. Pythagoras is often called the father of modern numerology because he formalized the idea that numbers carry distinct vibrations and meanings. But Babylonian, Egyptian, and Indian cultures were working with numerical symbolism long before he came along.\n[...]\nNumerology is at least 4,000 years old. Ancient Babylonian texts and Egyptian scrolls like the Book of the Master of the Secret House contain early numerical systems. The Pythagorean framework you encounter most often dates to around 500 B.C., making even the 'modern' version roughly 2,500 years old.\n[...]\n### What is the difference between Pythagorean and Chaldean numerology?\n[...]\nPythagorean numerology assigns numbers 1 through 9 to the letters of the alphabet in sequence and is the most widely used system today. Chaldean numerology, rooted in ancient Babylonian practice, assigns numbers based on the vibrational quality of each letter and does not use the number 9 in letter assignments. Most online calculators use the Pythagorean method.\n\n---\n\nTitle: History of Numerology - Kabbalah, Chaldean, Pythagorean, Chinese..\nURL: https://www.mypandit.com/numerology/history/\nPublished: 2021-06-04T09:58:33.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nSince the ages, many countries follow the basic concept of numerology. Countries like India, Greece, Italy, Japan, China, and ancient Egypt have already started using Numerology concepts. Chaldean Numerology and Kabbalah Numerology were the two methods often used in ancient times. The Greek philosopher Pythagoras later became the father of numerology. He is the one who developed the Pythagorean Numerology, which is also known as modern numerology. In the past, Pythagoras and other philosophers believed mathematics had more accessible concepts to classify than physics. They established schools for mathematics, astrology and music in Italy. Pythagoras was mostly fascinated with the principles of numbers and concepts of mathematics rather than solving problems. He firmly believed that numbers could expose the entire universe. However, his theories helped other philosophers to look into the concept, and even in mathematics, his theorems are the base of any high-level mathematics.\n[...]\nThe Chaldean system is mainly associated with every aspect of astrology. The Chaldeans were known as ancient Babylonian people, who used to recognize the energy change based on their way of speaking or thinking. This numerology is also associated with its branches of the Vedic system. This numerology works on only 1 to 8 numbers as the number 9 represents infinity. The Cha